>more or ill kill my self
Here is some concept art and information on the project! Please don't kill yourself!
>What is it?
An idea for an RPG I have, titled "Hello Again: Dockboy and Greaser."
"Hello Again: Dockboy and Greaser" is about two childhood friends, Charlie (A sheal) and Cass (A human male), who become separated following the collapse of society. Twelve years later, Cass returns to Avalon to find the island divided between two factions: The descendants of the sheals and humans of Avalon, and the grown-up members of an all-boys school known as Teskonet. The two factions are at an uneasy peace, thanks to Teskonet supplying Avalon with battle amplifiers (think Kids Next Door power armor) and lingerie. That all changes as soon as Cass arrives. Now, his uncle is taken captive by Avalon, Cass has to work with Charlie as well as their other friend Hortense (A southern shark, think a walking codfish) to find the Garden of Kessuin.
>Mechanics?
RPG Mechanics-wise, battle amplifiers provide an active bonus to characters, granting them unique attacks and defensive abilities. Meanwhile, Lingerie provides passive abilities for the whole group, mainly stat bonuses to charisma and healing.
>Gameplay?
Gameplay-wise, I'm thinking pokemon style RPG along with a minigame where you repair objects, such as burgers, boat engines, and assault rifles.
>But how far along are you with this game?
I have... concept art and the story plotted out. This is in the earliest stages of a project. It's not going to be done for at least a year, mainly because I have to go on a year-long hiatus in May. But I wanted to introduce the setting now so I can drop things here and there as I update and finish my other comics.

>>45660656
To add on to this anon,
In terms of the greeks, starting in the Peloponnesian wars to their defeat and conquest by the Romans, the greeks had linen armor called linothorax. A linothorax could be reinforced with bronze scales, usually on the right side of the linothorax because in their left hand would be their bronze-plated hoplon shield. Because the greeks focused heavily on rigid formations there was no need for excessive chest protection. It was assumed that the shield would provide the majority of defense and the armor act as a defense for anything that broke through. Shin protection, at least on the left leg was important because the hoplon couldn't cover those. Also, the left leg especially with Macedonian pikemen, was the leg they lead with when they marched and prepared to take the enemy. Gauntlets and helmets were necessary because of the times when the hoplon couldn't be moved fast enough to block a blow or when the hoplon itself was smaller in the case of the macedonian pike formations. Of course, the macedonian pike formations valued speed and maneuverability above all else, which is why despite the shield shrinking their formations kept the linen armour.
My source is Christopher Mathew's "An invincible beast:Understanding the Hellenistic Pike Phalanx in Action." The third chapter to be exact, titled "The Phalangite Panoply."

I am not one to hold a prejudice against any animal, but it is a plain fact that the spotted hyena is not well served by its appearance. It is ugly beyond redemption. Its thick neck and high shoulders that slope to the hindquarters look as if they've come from a discarded prototype for the giraffe, and its shaggy, coarse coat seems to have been patched together from the leftovers of creation. The colour is a bungled mix of tan, black, yellow, grey, with the spots having none of the classy ostentation of a leopard's rosettes; they look rather like the symptoms of a skin disease, a virulent form of mange. The head is broad and too massive, with a high forehead, like that of a bear, but suffering from a receding hairline, and with ears that look ridiculously mouse-like, large and round, when they haven't been torn off in battle. The mouth is forever open and panting. The nostrils are too big. The tail is scraggly and unwagging. The gait is shambling. All the parts put together look doglike, but like no dog anyone would want as a pet.
